            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "",
            "text": "<h2>ðŸš« Mistake #3: Wearing the Wrong Petticoat</h2><p>We often ignore the humble petticoat, but it can make or break your saree game. Ill-fitted petticoats cause bulges, lumps, or even drag the saree down.</p><h3><strong>âœ… How to fix it:</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Get it tailored to your waist.</strong> Drawstring is bestâ€”avoid elastics that slip.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>Match the fabric.</strong> Use cotton petticoats under cotton sarees, satin or silk under silks to avoid friction.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>Try shapewear petticoats.</strong> For a more sculpted look, just make sure you can breathe comfortably.</li></ul><p><strong>BONUS:</strong> You can also try the new cool style of wearing a saree without a petticoat, and to style a saree without a petticoat, read our blog: <a href=\"https://www.indyvogue.com/blogs/indyvogue-fashion-center/how-to-wear-a-saree-without-a-petticoat-yes-it-s-a-thing\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">How to Wear a Saree Without a Petticoat (Yes, Itâ€™s a Thing!) â€“ IndyVogue</span></a>Â </p><p></p><p></p><h2>ðŸš« Mistake #4: Over-Accessorizing or Wearing The Wrong Blouse</h2><p>That heavy necklace, chunky earrings, embroidered blouse, <em>and</em> loud palluâ€”all togetherâ€”can look OTT and cluttered.</p><h3><strong>âœ… How to fix it:</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Balance is key.</strong> If your saree is heavily embellished, go minimal with jewelry. If itâ€™s simple, glam up your accessories.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>Blouse fit matters.</strong> A too-tight blouse creates awkward bulges, while a loose one looks sloppy. Tailor it to your bust and shoulders perfectly.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><h2>ðŸš« Mistake #5: Ignoring Your Height & Body Type</h2><p>Certain drapes can overwhelm a petite frame or fail to flatter curvier silhouettes.</p><h3><strong>âœ… How to fix it:</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Petite ladies:</strong> Opt for slim, vertical drapes like the Nivi style. Keep the pallu narrow and long. Read this blog for more know-how - <a href=\"https://www.indyvogue.com/blogs/indyvogue-fashion-center/how-short-girls-can-look-tall-in-a-saree?srsltid=AfmBOopOCayeqcXLMSwlI6xBNkVV6Kr7w77jsepxSSGMW0EFySPh4KF9\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">https://www.indyvogue.com/blogs/indyvogue-fashion-center/how-short-girls-can-look-tall-in-a-saree?srsltid=AfmBOopOCayeqcXLMSwlI6xBNkVV6Kr7w77jsepxSSGMW0EFySPh4KF9</span></a> <br/><br/></li><li><strong>Curvy beauties:</strong> Try a seedha pallu or a belt to define your waist, with neat front pleats to smoothen the look.<br/><br/></li><li><strong>Tall girls:</strong> You can rock big, broad borders and lehenga-style multiple pleats like a dream.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><h2>ðŸš« Mistake #6: Skipping Final Checks</h2><p>Many of us forget to do a 360-degree spin in the mirror, resulting in a tucked-in phone bulge or a visible safety pin sticking out.</p><h3><strong>âœ… How to fix it:</strong></h3><ul><li>Before stepping out, stand straight and check all sides. Smooth out wrinkles. Make sure pleats fall evenly and your pallu flows gracefully.</li></ul>",
